    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{ 2 + \frac{2}{3}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{8}{3}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>When doing arithmetic with fractions, it is helpful to rewrite any integers as fractions:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 2 = \frac{2}{1} }</m></p>
<p>Next, to add two fractions, we need to find a common denominator. In this case, it is simply the second denominator <m>3</m>. We will rewrite the first fraction:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{2}{1} \amp = \frac{2 \cdot 3}{1 \cdot 3}\\ \amp = \frac{6}{3} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Finally, we add the numerators and keep the denominator unchanged. The whole process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   2 + \frac{2}{3}
        \amp = \frac{6}{3} + \frac{2}{3} \\
        \amp = \frac{6 + 2}{3} \\
        \amp = \frac{8}{3}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer to this question is  <m>{{\frac{8}{3}}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
